english:
  title: A Record of the Cloud Pavilion
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: "Master Uigong of the Avatamsaka school once sent me his poetry. Upon tasting its flavor, I recognized in him a monk of genuine poetic gift. After a long separation, he remained at Okcheon Temple and sent me a letter of several hundred words. His intent and expression were scarcely distinguishable from those of the finest literati. I understood then that Uigong harbored a profound dedication to poetry and prose. Long have I wished to hear his teachings directly.\n\nThis past summer, he came to the capital to visit and said to me: \"I have named my pavilion 'Cloud,' and I request that you compose a record for it.\" Since I was eager to hear his discourse, I asked him the meaning behind this name: \"Did you perhaps wish to sweep away the floating clouds that obscure form, sensation, perception, volition, and consciousness?\" \"No,\" he replied. \"Did you perhaps aspire to ascend through gradual practice to the Cloud of Dharma?\" \"No,\" he said again. Then, a sudden illumination struck me. These clouds—they must be the clouds beneath which he dwells.\n\nThe clouds that bring repose to one's form are the mountains' clouds; the clouds that stretch before wandering eyes are those of the endless sky. When the pavilion darkens, we know the clouds gather; when it brightens, we know they have passed. The pavilion overlooks a stream and cherishes the flowers blooming nearby; it faces the pines and loves the floating clouds above them. When the moon enters the pavilion and clouds veil its passage, the pure light burns all the brighter. When wind enters the pavilion and clouds follow in its wake, the chill deepens still more. \n\nThere, Uigong chants and sings. His verses grow ever more refined; his words ascend to realms of subtlety. Thus does he gain perpetually. When clouds gather in abundance and rain falls, the waters irrigate the people's fields, and merit ascends to merit heaven's rites—truly a great service to the world's transformation. In this, my teacher's heart of compassion for all beings shines forth. If this compassionate heart, thus firmly rooted, can pierce the clouds of illusion and ascend to the Cloud of Dharma, bringing the clouds of compassion to embrace the three thousand realms—such a day we may soon await. This is my record."
  footnotes:
    - The five skandhas (色受想行識—form, sensation, perception, volition, consciousness) represent the Buddhist analysis of all compounded phenomena; their transcendence marks spiritual advancement.
    - The 'Cloud of Dharma' (法雲) refers to the highest stage in the Bodhisattva path in Mahayana Buddhism, from which the rain of enlightenment falls upon all beings.
    - Lee Saek employs the image of clouds as a conceit for the monk's poetic and spiritual development, suggesting that clarity and obscurity, motion and stillness, are all instruments of enlightenment.
